aa(lp345
VWhen I found out that there are a whole bunch of industries
p346
aVthat didn't have copyright protection,
p347
aVI thought, "What exactly is the underlying logic?
p348
aVI want a picture." And the lawyers do not provide a picture,
p349
aVso I made one.
p350
aVThese are the two main
p351
aVsort of binary oppositions within the logic of copyright law.
p352
aVIt is more complex than this, but this will do.
p353
aVFirst: Is something an artistic object?
p354
aVThen it deserves protection.
p355
aVIs it a utilitarian object?
p356
aVThen no, it does not deserve protection.
p357
aVThis is a difficult, unstable binary.
p358
aa(lp359
VThe other one is: Is it an idea?
p360
aVIs it something that needs to
p361
aVfreely circulate in a free society?
p362
aVNo protection.
p363
aVOr is it a physically fixed
p364
aVexpression of an idea:
p365
aVsomething that somebody made
p366
aVand they deserve to own it for a while and make money from it?
p367
aVThe problem is that digital technology
p368
aVhas completely subverted the logic
p369
aVof this physically fixed, expression
p370
aVversus idea concept.
p371
aVNowadays,
p372
aVwe don't really recognize a book
p373
aVas something that sits on our shelf
p374
aVor music as something that is
p375
aVa physical object that we can hold.
p376
aVIt's a digital file.
p377
aVIt is barely tethered to any sort of
p378
aVphysical reality in our minds.
p379
aVAnd these things, because we can copy and transmit them so easily,
p380
aVactually circulate within our culture
p381
aVa lot more like ideas
p382
aVthan like physically instantiated objects.
